-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: 1 Kings — Part 2 (Chapters 12–22)
-- 3 difficulties × 11 chapters = 176 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 33
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 55
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 88
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 12 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 12, 'kids', 1, 'What did Rehoboam use to describe how he would punish the people compared to his father Solomon?', 'My father chastised you with whips, but I will chastise you with scorpions', 'My father was kind, but I will be kinder', 'My father used swords, but I will use spears', 'My father taxed you little, but I will tax you nothing', 'a', '1 Kings 12:11 — "And now whereas my father did lade you with a heavy yoke, I will add to your yoke: my father hath chastised you with whips, but I will chastise you with scorpions."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'kids', 2, 'Who became king over the ten northern tribes when the kingdom split?', 'Jeroboam', 'Rehoboam', 'Solomon', 'David', 'a', '1 Kings 12:20 — "And it came to pass, when all Israel heard that Jeroboam was come again, that they sent and called him unto the congregation, and made him king over all Israel."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'kids', 3, 'What animals did Jeroboam make for the people to worship?', 'Two golden calves', 'Two silver bulls', 'Two bronze eagles', 'Two golden lambs', 'a', '1 Kings 12:28 — "Whereupon the king took counsel, and made two calves of gold, and said unto them, It is too much for you to go up to Jerusalem: behold thy gods, O Israel, which brought thee up out of the land of Egypt."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 12, 'teens', 1, 'What advice did the old elders give Rehoboam that he rejected?', 'To serve the people and speak good words to them so they would serve him forever', 'To raise taxes immediately', 'To build a stronger army', 'To move the capital city', 'a', '1 Kings 12:7 — "And they spake unto him, saying, If thou wilt be a servant unto this people this day, and wilt serve them, and answer them, and speak good words to them, then they will be thy servants for ever."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'teens', 2, 'What was the rallying cry of Israel when they rebelled against Rehoboam?', '"What portion have we in David? neither have we inheritance in the son of Jesse: to your tents, O Israel"', '"God save the king of Israel"', '"Down with the house of Solomon"', '"We will follow Jeroboam to war"', 'a', '1 Kings 12:16 — "So when all Israel saw that the king hearkened not unto them, the people answered the king, saying, What portion have we in David? neither have we inheritance in the son of Jesse: to your tents, O Israel: now see to thine own house, David."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'teens', 3, 'Why did Jeroboam set up golden calves at Dan and Bethel?', 'So the people would not go to Jerusalem to worship and return their hearts to Rehoboam', 'Because Moses had commanded it', 'Because God appeared to him in a vision', 'Because the Levites requested new altars', 'a', '1 Kings 12:27 — "If this people go up to do sacrifice in the house of the LORD at Jerusalem, then shall the heart of this people turn again unto their lord, even unto Rehoboam king of Judah."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'teens', 4, 'How long did Rehoboam wait before consulting advisors about attacking Israel to reunite the kingdom?', 'Three days, as the people requested', 'One week', 'One year', 'One month', 'a', '1 Kings 12:5 — "And he said unto them, Depart yet for three days, then come again to me. And the people departed."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'teens', 5, 'What message from God stopped Rehoboam from going to war against Israel?', 'That the division was God''s doing and they should not fight against their brethren', 'That Jeroboam was stronger and would win', 'That the people of Israel had repented', 'That an enemy nation was approaching', 'a', '1 Kings 12:24 — "Thus saith the LORD, Ye shall not go up, nor fight against your brethren the children of Israel: return every man to his house; for this thing is from me."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 1, 'What was the cause of the kingdom''s division according to the narrator?', 'It was a turn of affairs brought about by the LORD to fulfil the word He had spoken by Ahijah to Jeroboam', 'It was purely a political miscalculation by Rehoboam', 'It was Jeroboam''s military superiority', 'It was the failure of Solomon''s economic policies', 'a', '1 Kings 12:15 — "Wherefore the king hearkened not unto the people; for the cause was from the LORD, that he might perform his saying, which the LORD spake by Ahijah the Shilonite unto Jeroboam the son of Nebat."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 2, 'Who was Adoram and what happened to him when Rehoboam sent him to Israel?', 'He was over the tribute and was stoned to death by all Israel', 'He was a prophet who was ignored', 'He was a general who surrendered', 'He was a priest who was imprisoned', 'a', '1 Kings 12:18 — "Then king Rehoboam sent Adoram, who was over the tribute; and all Israel stoned him with stones, that he died. Therefore king Rehoboam made speed to get him up to his chariot, to flee to Jerusalem."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 3, 'Over which tribes did Rehoboam continue to reign after the division?', 'Only the tribe of Judah', 'Judah and Benjamin', 'Judah, Benjamin, and Simeon', 'All twelve tribes', 'a', '1 Kings 12:20 — "There was none that followed the house of David, but the tribe of Judah only."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 4, 'What was the sin of Jeroboam''s new religious system beyond the golden calves?', 'He made priests from among all the people who were not of the sons of Levi', 'He abolished the Passover feast', 'He destroyed the ark of the covenant', 'He built a new temple in Samaria', 'a', '1 Kings 12:31 — "And he made an house of high places, and made priests of the lowest of the people, which were not of the sons of Levi."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 5, 'What feast did Jeroboam institute and when did he set it?', 'A feast in the eighth month, on the fifteenth day, like the feast in Judah — ordained by himself', 'A feast in the first month to celebrate his coronation', 'A weekly feast every Sabbath at Bethel', 'A yearly fast on the Day of Atonement', 'a', '1 Kings 12:32-33 — "And Jeroboam ordained a feast in the eighth month, on the fifteenth day of the month, like unto the feast that is in Judah, and he offered upon the altar. So did he in Bethel, sacrificing unto the calves that he had made."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 6, 'What did Jeroboam tell the young men who grew up with him rather than the elders?', 'He accepted their harsh advice to increase the yoke beyond his father''s burdens', 'He rejected their counsel for the elders'' wisdom', 'He asked them to negotiate with Jeroboam', 'He sent them as ambassadors to Egypt', 'a', '1 Kings 12:10-11 — "And the young men that were grown up with him spake unto him, saying... My little finger shall be thicker than my father''s loins."'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 7, 'What does the placement of one calf in Dan and one in Bethel suggest geographically?', 'They marked the northern and southern boundaries of the northern kingdom, creating a national worship system', 'They were placed near the two largest cities for convenience', 'They replaced the two tablets of the law', 'They corresponded to the two cherubim in Solomon''s temple', 'a', '1 Kings 12:29 — "And he set the one in Bethel, and the other put he in Dan." Dan was at the far north and Bethel at the southern edge of the kingdom — a calculated religious geography.'),
('1 Kings', 12, 'adults', 8, 'How does Jeroboam''s golden calf proclamation echo the Exodus narrative?', 'He repeated the words of Aaron at Sinai: "behold thy gods, O Israel, which brought thee up out of the land of Egypt" — a deliberate inversion of the Exodus', 'He quoted the Song of Moses from Deuteronomy', 'He referenced the pillar of cloud and fire', 'He recited the Ten Commandments as a cover', 'a', '1 Kings 12:28 — "Behold thy gods, O Israel, which brought thee up out of the land of Egypt" (cf. Exodus 32:4). The verbal parallel condemns Jeroboam by linking his act to Israel''s greatest apostasy.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 13 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 13, 'kids', 1, 'A man of God came to Bethel and cried against the altar. What happened to Jeroboam''s hand when he stretched it out to seize him?', 'It dried up and he could not pull it back to him', 'It was cut off by a sword', 'It became very cold', 'It turned to stone', 'a', '1 Kings 13:4 — "And his hand, which he put forth against him, dried up, so that he could not pull it in again to him."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'kids', 2, 'What happened to the altar at Bethel as a sign?', 'It split apart and the ashes poured out', 'It caught on fire', 'It sank into the ground', 'It turned to gold', 'a', '1 Kings 13:5 — "The altar also was rent, and the ashes poured out from the altar, according to the sign which the man of God had given by the word of the LORD."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'kids', 3, 'What animal killed the man of God after he disobeyed God''s command?', 'A lion', 'A bear', 'A wolf', 'An eagle', 'a', '1 Kings 13:24 — "And when he was gone, a lion met him by the way, and slew him: and his carcase was cast in the way, and the ass stood by it, the lion also stood by the carcase."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 13, 'teens', 1, 'What future king did the man of God prophesy would desecrate Jeroboam''s altar at Bethel?', 'Josiah', 'Hezekiah', 'Jehu', 'Asa', 'a', '1 Kings 13:2 — "And he cried against the altar in the word of the LORD, and said, O altar, altar, thus saith the LORD; Behold, a child shall be born unto the house of David, Josiah by name."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'teens', 2, 'What were God''s strict instructions to the man of God from Judah?', 'He must not eat bread or drink water in Bethel and must return by a different way', 'He must preach at every city in Israel', 'He must stay in Bethel for seven days', 'He must not speak to King Jeroboam', 'a', '1 Kings 13:9 — "For so was it charged me by the word of the LORD, saying, Eat no bread, nor drink water, nor turn again by the same way that thou camest."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'teens', 3, 'How did the old prophet of Bethel deceive the man of God into returning with him?', 'He falsely claimed an angel had told him to bring the man back to eat and drink with him', 'He offered him gold and silver', 'He threatened to report him to the king', 'He told him there was a shorter road home', 'a', '1 Kings 13:18 — "He said unto him, I am a prophet also as thou art; and an angel spake unto me by the word of the LORD, saying, Bring him back with thee into thine house, that he may eat bread and drink water. But he lied unto him."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'teens', 4, 'What did the old prophet say when he saw the man of God''s body after the lion killed him?', 'He mourned and said the man of God was disobedient and God had delivered him to the lion', 'He rejoiced because his deception had worked', 'He buried him in his own tomb and mourned him as his brother', 'He asked God to raise him from the dead', 'a', '1 Kings 13:26 — "And when the prophet that brought him back from the way heard thereof, he said, It is the man of God, who was disobedient unto the word of the LORD: therefore the LORD hath delivered him unto the lion, which hath torn him, and slain him."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'teens', 5, 'What remarkable detail showed this was a supernatural event involving the lion?', 'The lion did not eat the body and did not harm the donkey — it just stood by the carcase', 'The lion spoke with a human voice', 'The lion turned white after killing him', 'The lion immediately disappeared', 'a', '1 Kings 13:28 — "And he went and found his carcase cast in the way, and the ass and the lion standing by the carcase: the lion had not eaten the carcase, nor torn the ass."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 1, 'What specific prophecy about Josiah is given at the altar of Bethel, and how many years before its fulfillment was it spoken?', 'That Josiah would burn human bones on it — spoken approximately 300 years before its fulfillment under Josiah (2 Kings 23)', 'That Josiah would rebuild the altar in glory', 'That Josiah would make Bethel the new capital', 'That Josiah would find the Book of the Law there', 'a', '1 Kings 13:2 — "Behold, a child shall be born unto the house of David, Josiah by name; and upon thee shall he offer the priests of the high places that burn incense upon thee, and men''s bones shall be burnt upon thee." This was fulfilled around 300 years later in 2 Kings 23:15-16.'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 2, 'How was Jeroboam''s hand restored and what does this reveal about God''s character in this episode?', 'The man of God prayed and God healed it — showing God''s mercy even toward apostate kings alongside His firm judgment', 'It was healed by the old prophet''s touch', 'It healed naturally after three days', 'It was never healed in the chapter', 'a', '1 Kings 13:6 — "And the king answered and said unto the man of God, Intreat now the face of the LORD thy God, and pray for me, that my hand may be restored me again. And the man of God besought the LORD, and the king''s hand was restored him again."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 3, 'What theological principle does the man of God''s death illustrate about partial obedience?', 'That disobeying God''s word — even when deceived by a "prophet" — carries fatal consequences; believers are responsible to test all words against God''s revealed command', 'That prophets are always to be trusted', 'That God punishes innocent mistakes without mercy', 'That only kings are held accountable for disobedience', 'a', '1 Kings 13:26 — "He is the man of God, who was disobedient unto the word of the LORD." The man had a direct word from God yet accepted a contradictory claim without testing it (cf. Galatians 1:8).'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 4, 'Why did the old prophet request to be buried in the same tomb as the man of God?', 'Because he believed the prophecy against Bethel''s altar was true and wanted his bones to be spared alongside the man of God''s bones', 'Because he felt guilty for causing his death', 'Because it was customary to bury prophets together', 'Because his family tomb had no more room', 'a', '1 Kings 13:31-32 — "Lay my bones beside his bones: For the saying which he cried by the word of the LORD against the altar in Bethel... shall surely come to pass." This was fulfilled in 2 Kings 23:17-18.'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 5, 'What does the behavior of the lion — not eating the corpse and standing guard — communicate in its ancient Near Eastern context?', 'It authenticated the divine judgment; the lion was an instrument of God''s verdict, not a predator acting naturally, testifying to the supernatural nature of the punishment', 'It showed the lion was tame and domesticated', 'It indicated the man of God was poisonous', 'It was a coincidence with no theological meaning', 'a', '1 Kings 13:28 — "The lion had not eaten the carcase, nor torn the ass." In the ancient world, lions eating corpses was the ultimate desecration. The lion''s restraint marked this death as divine judgment, not random violence.'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 6, 'What was Jeroboam''s response to all these signs — the withered hand, the restored hand, the split altar — regarding his sinful practices?', 'He did not return from his evil way but made priests from all classes of people for the high places', 'He repented and removed the golden calves', 'He sought Ahijah the prophet for guidance', 'He went to Jerusalem to worship at the temple', 'a', '1 Kings 13:33 — "After this thing Jeroboam returned not from his evil way, but made again of the lowest of the people priests of the high places."'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 7, 'What did the old prophet say to his sons before retrieving the body, and what does this reveal?', 'He told them to saddle the donkey — his quick response and mourning suggest he knew the word against Bethel was genuine, making his deception all the more culpable', 'He commanded them to warn the king', 'He told them to inform Jerusalem', 'He asked them to pray for the dead man''s resurrection', 'a', '1 Kings 13:27 — "And he spake to his sons, saying, Saddle me the ass. And they saddled him." His prompt mourning (v.30) reveals he accepted the man''s prophetic authenticity — exposing his own deception as inexcusable.'),
('1 Kings', 13, 'adults', 8, 'How does this chapter function as a literary hinge in 1 Kings regarding the fate of Jeroboam''s dynasty?', 'It names the ultimate executor of judgment (Josiah) before describing Jeroboam''s continued apostasy, framing all subsequent northern kingdom history under the shadow of inevitable divine reckoning', 'It simply records a curious incident with a lion', 'It shows God was indifferent to Jeroboam''s sins', 'It suggests Bethel would eventually become a holy site', 'a', '1 Kings 13:2, 33-34 — The Josiah prophecy and the editorial note that this "became sin unto the house of Jeroboam, even to cut it off, and to destroy it from off the face of the earth" bracket the chapter with inescapable doom.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 14 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 14, 'kids', 1, 'Why did Jeroboam send his wife to the prophet Ahijah?', 'Because his son was sick and he wanted to know if the boy would recover', 'Because he wanted to learn a new prophecy', 'Because she wanted to become a prophetess', 'Because Ahijah had asked to see her', 'a', '1 Kings 14:1-3 — "At that time Abijah the son of Jeroboam fell sick. And Jeroboam said to his wife, Arise, I pray thee, and disguise thyself, that thou be not known to be the wife of Jeroboam; and get thee to Shiloh: behold, there is Ahijah the prophet."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'kids', 2, 'How did the blind prophet Ahijah know who was at the door before she told him?', 'God had told him she was coming and what to say', 'He heard her familiar voice', 'A servant had seen her coming', 'He recognised her footsteps', 'a', '1 Kings 14:5 — "And the LORD said unto Ahijah, Behold, the wife of Jeroboam cometh to ask a thing of thee for her son; for he is sick: thus and thus shalt thou say unto her."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'kids', 3, 'What foreign king attacked Jerusalem and took away the treasures of the temple during Rehoboam''s reign?', 'Shishak king of Egypt', 'Ben-hadad king of Syria', 'Hiram king of Tyre', 'Mesha king of Moab', 'a', '1 Kings 14:25-26 — "And it came to pass in the fifth year of king Rehoboam, that Shishak king of Egypt came up against Jerusalem: And he took away the treasures of the house of the LORD, and the treasures of the king''s house."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 14, 'teens', 1, 'What did Ahijah prophesy would happen to Jeroboam''s son Abijah?', 'He would die when his mother''s feet entered the city, and he alone of Jeroboam''s house would come to the grave in peace', 'He would recover and become a great king', 'He would be carried to Jerusalem to be healed', 'He would outlive his father and become king', 'a', '1 Kings 14:12-13 — "Arise thou therefore, get thee to thine own house: and when thy feet enter into the city, the child shall die... And all Israel shall mourn for him, and bury him: for he only of Jeroboam shall come to the grave."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'teens', 2, 'What did Ahijah say God compared Jeroboam''s sins to?', 'All the evil of those who were before him — he had cast God behind his back and made other gods', 'The sins of Pharaoh in Egypt', 'The sins of the Canaanites before Israel', 'The minor sins of David', 'a', '1 Kings 14:9 — "But hast done evil above all that were before thee: for thou hast gone and made thee other gods, and molten images, to provoke me to anger, and hast cast me behind thy back."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'teens', 3, 'What does Ahijah say God will do to the house of Jeroboam?', 'Cut it off and take it away as a man takes away dung, until it is all gone', 'Restore it if Jeroboam repents', 'Preserve it for David''s sake', 'Transfer the throne to another tribe', 'a', '1 Kings 14:10 — "Therefore, behold, I will bring evil upon the house of Jeroboam, and will cut off from Jeroboam him that pisseth against the wall... as a man taketh away dung, till it be all gone."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'teens', 4, 'What sins of Judah under Rehoboam are mentioned in this chapter?', 'High places, images, groves, and sodomites in the land — provoking God more than all their fathers', 'Only idol worship at the temple', 'Neglect of the Sabbath', 'Refusal to pay tithes', 'a', '1 Kings 14:23-24 — "For they also built them high places, and images, and groves, on every high hill, and under every green tree. And there were also sodomites in the land: and they did according to all the abominations of the nations."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'teens', 5, 'What replaced the golden shields Solomon had made after Shishak took them away?', 'Rehoboam made bronze shields in their place', 'He made new golden ones immediately', 'He left the entrances unguarded', 'He bought shields from Egypt', 'a', '1 Kings 14:27 — "And king Rehoboam made in their stead brasen shields, and committed them into the hands of the chief of the guard."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 1, 'What was the theological irony of Jeroboam disguising his wife to consult Ahijah?', 'He feared the prophet who had originally given him the kingdom, revealing that he knew his idolatry had forfeited God''s favour — his deception showed guilt, not faith', 'He simply did not want political embarrassment', 'He was testing the prophet''s abilities', 'He respected the prophet too much to impose on him', 'a', '1 Kings 14:2 — "Arise, I pray thee, and disguise thyself, that thou be not known to be the wife of Jeroboam." It was Ahijah who had torn the garment and promised Jeroboam the kingdom (1 Kings 11:29-31), making this consultation deeply ironic.'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 2, 'What did Ahijah say God had originally offered Jeroboam that he had failed to receive?', 'To build him a sure house as David''s if he kept God''s commandments — the same conditional promise given to David', 'Unconditional rulership over all twelve tribes', 'A special priestly dynasty', 'Permanent protection from all enemies', 'a', '1 Kings 14:7-8 — "I exalted thee from among the people, and made thee prince over my people Israel, And rent the kingdom away from the house of David, and gave it thee: and yet thou hast not been as my servant David."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 3, 'How does Ahijah describe what would happen to Israel because of Jeroboam''s sins?', 'God would smite Israel as a reed is shaken in water, root them up from the good land, and scatter them beyond the river', 'God would send a single battle to discipline them', 'God would temporarily remove their king', 'God would send seven years of famine', 'a', '1 Kings 14:15 — "For the LORD shall smite Israel, as a reed is shaken in the water, and he shall root up Israel out of this good land, which he gave to their fathers, and shall scatter them beyond the river."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 4, 'The phrase "beyond the river" in Ahijah''s prophecy is a reference to what eventual historical event?', 'The Assyrian exile — the deportation of northern Israel beyond the Euphrates, fulfilled in 722 BC under Shalmaneser V and Sargon II', 'The Babylonian captivity of Judah', 'A temporary military defeat by Syria', 'The Exodus from Egypt in reverse', 'a', '1 Kings 14:15 — "He shall root up Israel out of this good land... and shall scatter them beyond the river." This was fulfilled when Assyria deported the northern tribes (2 Kings 17:6), approximately 200 years after this prophecy.'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 5, 'What does the narrative''s description of Rehoboam''s mother as "Naamah an Ammonitess" contribute theologically?', 'It links Rehoboam''s idolatrous reign back to Solomon''s foreign wives and their foreign gods — the sin of the father bearing fruit in the son', 'It is simply a genealogical notation', 'It demonstrates Rehoboam''s diplomatic heritage', 'It shows God''s grace to foreign nations', 'a', '1 Kings 14:21 — "And his mother''s name was Naamah an Ammonitess." Solomon''s Ammonite wives had led him to Molech worship (1 Kings 11:1,7). Rehoboam''s mother was one of those women, explaining the spiritual trajectory of his reign.'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 6, 'What continual state existed between Rehoboam and Jeroboam throughout their reigns?', 'Continual war — there was war between Rehoboam and Jeroboam all their days', 'An uneasy peace maintained by treaty', 'Regular diplomatic exchanges', 'Occasional border skirmishes only', 'a', '1 Kings 14:30 — "And there was war between Rehoboam and Jeroboam all their days."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 7, 'What does Ahijah''s description of Israel''s sins as groves (Asherah poles) on "every high hill and under every green tree" echo?', 'The Deuteronomic warnings against precisely this form of Canaanite worship — showing Israel had fully adopted the abominations God had told them to destroy', 'A neutral description of landscaping practices', 'The fulfillment of the planting festivals', 'A positive sign of agricultural prosperity', 'a', '1 Kings 14:23 — "They also built them high places, and images, and groves, on every high hill, and under every green tree." Compare Deuteronomy 12:2: "Ye shall utterly destroy all the places, wherein the nations which ye shall possess served their gods, upon the high mountains."'),
('1 Kings', 14, 'adults', 8, 'What does the replacement of Solomon''s golden shields with bronze shields symbolise in the broader narrative of 1 Kings?', 'The progressive material and spiritual decline of the Davidic kingdom — from gold to bronze mirrors the trajectory from Solomon''s glory to Rehoboam''s diminished reign', 'Simply a practical economic decision', 'A military improvement since bronze was stronger', 'God''s judgment specifically on luxury', 'a', '1 Kings 14:26-27 — Solomon had "made two hundred targets of beaten gold" (1 Kings 10:16), which Shishak took. Rehoboam made brass replacements — a vivid symbol of the kingdom''s decline from Solomonic splendour.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 15 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 15, 'kids', 1, 'What good king of Judah removed idols and tried to follow God like his ancestor David?', 'Asa', 'Abijam', 'Baasha', 'Nadab', 'a', '1 Kings 15:11 — "And Asa did that which was right in the eyes of the LORD, as did David his father."'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'kids', 2, 'What relative did King Asa remove from being queen because she had made an idol?', 'His grandmother Maachah', 'His mother Naamah', 'His sister Tamar', 'His aunt Abigail', 'a', '1 Kings 15:13 — "And also Maachah his mother, even her he removed from being queen, because she had made an idol in a grove; and Asa destroyed her idol, and burnt it by the brook Kidron."'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'kids', 3, 'Who became king of Israel after Jeroboam''s son Nadab was killed?', 'Baasha', 'Omri', 'Zimri', 'Elah', 'a', '1 Kings 15:28 — "Even in the third year of Asa king of Judah did Baasha slay him, and reigned in his stead."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 15, 'teens', 1, 'Why was Abijam''s heart not perfect with God, yet God still gave him a lamp in Jerusalem?', 'For David''s sake — God had promised to preserve David''s line in Jerusalem', 'Because Abijam built a great temple', 'Because the people loved him greatly', 'Because he defeated all his enemies', 'a', '1 Kings 15:4-5 — "Nevertheless for David''s sake did the LORD his God give him a lamp in Jerusalem... Because David did that which was right in the eyes of the LORD, and turned not aside from any thing that he commanded him all the days of his life, save only in the matter of Uriah the Hittite."'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'teens', 2, 'What items did Asa bring into the house of the LORD?', 'The things his father had dedicated, and silver and gold and vessels', 'New golden lampstands he had made himself', 'The ark from Shiloh', 'Spices and incense from Arabia', 'a', '1 Kings 15:15 — "And he brought in the things which his father had dedicated, and the things which himself had dedicated, into the house of the LORD, silver, and gold, and vessels."'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'teens', 3, 'What deal did Asa of Judah make with Ben-hadad king of Syria?', 'He sent silver and gold to Ben-hadad asking him to break his league with Baasha and attack northern Israel instead', 'He gave Ben-hadad his daughter in marriage', 'He agreed to pay yearly tribute to Syria', 'He offered Ben-hadad cities in the Negev', 'a', '1 Kings 15:18-19 — "Then Asa took all the silver and the gold that were left in the treasures of the house of the LORD, and the treasures of the king''s house, and delivered them into the hand of his servants: and king Asa sent them to Ben-hadad... saying, There is a league between me and thee."'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'teens', 4, 'What did Baasha fulfil by wiping out all the house of Jeroboam?', 'The prophecy of Ahijah the Shilonite concerning Jeroboam''s house', 'His own personal ambition without any prophetic significance', 'A command given to him by Moses in the law', 'A treaty obligation with Egypt', 'a', '1 Kings 15:29 — "And it came to pass, when he reigned, that he smote all the house of Jeroboam; he left not to Jeroboam any that breathed, until he had destroyed him, according unto the saying of the LORD, which he spake by his servant Ahijah the Shilonite."'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'teens', 5, 'What did Asa do with the materials Baasha had been using to build Ramah after Ben-hadad attacked Israel?', 'He used the building stones and timber to build Geba of Benjamin and Mizpah', 'He burned them all', 'He sent them to Jerusalem for the temple', 'He sold them to pay Ben-hadad', 'a', '1 Kings 15:22 — "Then king Asa made a proclamation throughout all Judah; none was exempted: and they took away the stones of Ramah, and the timber thereof, wherewith Baasha had builded; and king Asa built with them Geba of Benjamin, and Mizpah."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 1, 'What does the repeated phrase "his heart was not perfect with the LORD his God" reveal about the Deuteronomistic evaluation of kings?', 'It establishes wholehearted exclusive loyalty to Yahweh as the sole criterion of good kingship — a theological standard derived from the Shema (Deuteronomy 6:4-5)', 'It refers only to ritual purity', 'It measures kings by military success', 'It evaluates economic policies', 'a', '1 Kings 15:3 — "His heart was not perfect with the LORD his God, as the heart of David his father." The Deuteronomistic Historian uses this formula throughout 1-2 Kings as the primary lens for evaluating every monarch.'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 2, 'What specific exception does the narrator make when praising David as the standard for kings?', 'The matter of Uriah the Hittite — showing the narrator''s historical honesty even while using David as the ideal benchmark', 'David''s taking of multiple wives', 'David''s failure to build the temple', 'David''s flight from Saul', 'a', '1 Kings 15:5 — "David did that which was right in the eyes of the LORD, and turned not aside from any thing that he commanded him all the days of his life, save only in the matter of Uriah the Hittite." This parenthetical acknowledgement prevents an idealised reading of David.'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 3, 'What does Asa''s removal of the male cult prostitutes (sodomites) and idols suggest about the depth of religious corruption inherited from Rehoboam?', 'It indicates that Canaanite fertility religion had been institutionalised in Judah since Rehoboam''s reign and required deliberate royal action to dismantle', 'It was a minor housekeeping matter', 'It shows the people had chosen this worship freely', 'It demonstrates Asa had authority only over religious matters', 'a', '1 Kings 15:12 — "And he took away the sodomites out of the land, and removed all the idols that his fathers had made." Rehoboam''s reign had introduced sodomites (1 Kings 14:24); Asa''s reforms show how entrenched this had become in a single generation.'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 4, 'What tension does Asa''s alliance with Ben-hadad create theologically within his otherwise positive evaluation?', 'He used the temple treasury to buy Syrian military help rather than trusting God — the Chronicler explicitly condemns this as faithlessness (2 Chronicles 16:7-9)', 'It was a neutral diplomatic achievement', 'It demonstrated wise foreign policy', 'It fulfilled a Mosaic command about treaties', 'a', '1 Kings 15:18 — "Then Asa took all the silver and the gold that were left in the treasures of the house of the LORD." The stripping of the temple treasury to fund a foreign alliance is theologically problematic, especially since the same treasury Shishak had not completely emptied was now voluntarily handed over.'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 5, 'How does Nadab''s assassination by Baasha fulfil Ahijah''s prophecy and what pattern does it establish for the northern kingdom?', 'It fulfils the word against Jeroboam''s house and establishes a recurring pattern of violent dynastic change — unlike Judah where the Davidic covenant provided relative stability', 'It was simply political instability with no theological meaning', 'It shows God preferred Baasha to Jeroboam''s line', 'It established a tradition of peaceful succession', 'a', '1 Kings 15:29-30 — "He smote all the house of Jeroboam... according unto the saying of the LORD." Every subsequent northern dynasty would end violently, in contrast to Judah''s Davidic continuity, underscoring the importance of the Davidic covenant.'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 6, 'What does the war between Asa and Baasha throughout their reigns reveal about the political geography of the divided kingdom?', 'The border between Judah and Israel ran through Benjamin''s territory near Ramah — a strategic flashpoint whose control determined the security of both capitals', 'The two kingdoms had completely separate trade routes', 'There was no economic interaction between the kingdoms', 'The Philistines instigated all conflicts between them', 'a', '1 Kings 15:16-17 — "And there was war between Asa and Baasha king of Israel all their days. And Baasha king of Israel went up against Judah, and built Ramah." Ramah was only five miles north of Jerusalem — Baasha''s fortification there threatened to blockade the capital.'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 7, 'How many years did Asa reign and what does this length suggest within the theological framework of 1 Kings?', 'Forty-one years — among the longest reigns in Judah, which the narrative implicitly connects to his faithfulness, echoing the blessing-curse structure of Deuteronomy', 'Twenty years, showing God''s limited approval', 'Twelve years, corresponding to the twelve tribes', 'Eight years, a brief reign due to his sins', 'a', '1 Kings 15:10 — "And forty and one years reigned he in Jerusalem." Asa''s long reign stands in implicit contrast to wicked northern kings who ruled only briefly, though the text never makes this explicit — readers familiar with Deuteronomic theology would recognise the pattern.'),
('1 Kings', 15, 'adults', 8, 'What does the phrase "nevertheless Asa''s heart was perfect with the LORD all his days" suggest about the Deuteronomistic standard when compared to earlier kings?', 'It signals a wholehearted personal devotion even though Asa did not remove all the high places — the historian distinguishes between structural religious failures and sincere personal fidelity', 'It means Asa committed no sins whatsoever', 'It means the high places were acceptable to God', 'It applies only to Asa''s last years', 'a', '1 Kings 15:14 — "But the high places were not removed: nevertheless Asa''s heart was perfect with the LORD all his days." This nuanced evaluation shows the historian can award positive verdicts despite incomplete reforms, provided personal loyalty to Yahweh is genuine.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 16 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 16, 'kids', 1, 'How many days did King Zimri reign over Israel before he died?', 'Seven days', 'Forty days', 'One year', 'Six months', 'a', '1 Kings 16:15 — "In the twenty and seventh year of Asa king of Judah did Zimri reign seven days in Tirzah."'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'kids', 2, 'What wicked queen did King Ahab marry?', 'Jezebel', 'Athaliah', 'Bathsheba', 'Michal', 'a', '1 Kings 16:31 — "And it came to pass, as if it had been a light thing for him to walk in the sins of Jeroboam the son of Nebat, that he took to wife Jezebel the daughter of Ethbaal king of the Zidonians."'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'kids', 3, 'What false god did Ahab build a temple for in Samaria?', 'Baal', 'Molech', 'Dagon', 'Chemosh', 'a', '1 Kings 16:32 — "And he reared up an altar for Baal in the house of Baal, which he had built in Samaria."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 16, 'teens', 1, 'What did the prophet Jehu son of Hanani prophesy against Baasha?', 'That God would make his house like the house of Jeroboam because he walked in Jeroboam''s ways and made Israel sin', 'That Baasha would be victorious over Judah', 'That his son would reign wisely', 'That Israel would return to worshipping God', 'a', '1 Kings 16:3-4 — "Behold, I will take away the posterity of Baasha, and the posterity of his house; and will make thy house like the house of Jeroboam the son of Nebat."'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'teens', 2, 'How did Zimri seize the throne from King Elah?', 'He killed Elah while he was drunk in the house of Arza his steward in Tirzah', 'He led a military revolt at the border', 'He challenged Elah to personal combat', 'He bribed the palace guards', 'a', '1 Kings 16:9-10 — "And his servant Zimri, captain of half his chariots, conspired against him, as he was in Tirzah, drinking himself drunk in the house of Arza steward of his house in Tirzah. And Zimri went in and smote him, and killed him."'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'teens', 3, 'How did Zimri die when Omri''s forces besieged Tirzah?', 'He went into the king''s palace and burned it over himself with fire', 'He fled to Syria and was captured', 'He was killed in battle at the city gate', 'He surrendered and was executed', 'a', '1 Kings 16:18 — "And it came to pass, when Zimri saw that the city was taken, that he went into the palace of the king''s house, and burnt the king''s house over him with fire, and died."'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'teens', 4, 'What ancient curse was fulfilled when Hiel of Bethel rebuilt Jericho?', 'Joshua''s curse — he lost his firstborn when he laid the foundation and his youngest when he set up the gates', 'A prophecy by Moses about rebuilding cities', 'A curse from the time of the judges', 'A warning given to Solomon about Jericho', 'a', '1 Kings 16:34 — "In his days did Hiel the Bethelite build Jericho: he laid the foundation thereof in Abiram his firstborn, and set up the gates thereof in his youngest son Segub, according to the word of the LORD, which he spake by Joshua the son of Nun."'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'teens', 5, 'How does the narrator summarise Ahab''s wickedness compared to all the kings before him?', 'He did more to provoke the LORD God of Israel to anger than all the kings of Israel that were before him', 'He was slightly worse than Jeroboam', 'He was equal in wickedness to Omri', 'He was bad only because of Jezebel''s influence', 'a', '1 Kings 16:33 — "And Ahab made a grove; and Ahab did more to provoke the LORD God of Israel to anger than all the kings of Israel that were before him."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 1, 'What theological irony exists in God using Baasha to destroy Jeroboam''s house and then pronouncing the same judgment on Baasha?', 'Baasha was God''s instrument of judgment against Jeroboam yet himself walked in Jeroboam''s sins — the tool of judgment became subject to the same judgment, showing God''s impartiality', 'God made an error in choosing Baasha', 'Baasha was simply unlucky in his successors', 'God preferred the house of Omri over Baasha', 'a', '1 Kings 16:7 — "And also by the hand of the prophet Jehu the son of Hanani came the word of the LORD against Baasha and against his house, even for all the evil that he did in the sight of the LORD... and because he killed him." Baasha committed the same sin he was used to punish.'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 2, 'What does Omri''s purchase of Samaria and its development as Israel''s capital reveal about his political significance beyond the brief biblical account?', 'Omri was a major regional power — Assyrian records called the northern kingdom "the house of Omri" for over a century after his dynasty ended, indicating his international importance', 'Omri was insignificant and the capital choice was accidental', 'Samaria had been a holy site since the judges', 'The purchase was a sign of weakness', 'a', '1 Kings 16:24 — "And he bought the hill Samaria of Shemer for two talents of silver, and built on the hill, and called the name of the city which he built, after the name of Shemer, owner of the hill, Samaria." The Assyrian "bit Humri" (house of Omri) designation demonstrates his lasting political legacy despite his brief biblical treatment.'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 3, 'What does Ahab''s marriage to Jezebel represent in terms of the religious trajectory of Israel?', 'It introduced state-sponsored Phoenician Baal worship at the highest level, moving beyond Jeroboam''s nationalist golden calf religion to wholesale foreign paganism', 'A politically neutral diplomatic marriage', 'A minor deviation from the norm of foreign wives', 'An improvement since Jezebel brought cultural sophistication', 'a', '1 Kings 16:31 — "He took to wife Jezebel the daughter of Ethbaal king of the Zidonians, and went and served Baal, and worshipped him." Ethbaal was a priest of Astarte who became king — Jezebel came from a priestly-royal family with total commitment to Phoenician religion.'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 4, 'What pattern is established by the rapid succession of dynasties — Jeroboam, Baasha, Zimri, Omri — in the northern kingdom?', 'Political instability through violent usurpation, contrasting sharply with Judah''s Davidic covenant that provided dynastic continuity — the northern kingdom had no theological basis for stable succession', 'Normal ancient Near Eastern political succession', 'Evidence that God had abandoned Israel completely', 'Proof that democracy was the preferred system', 'a', '1 Kings 16:8-28 covers four kings in rapid succession, each overthrowing the previous. The Davidic covenant (2 Samuel 7) provided Judah with a theological framework for kingship that the north lacked entirely.'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 5, 'How does the fulfillment of Joshua''s Jericho curse (Joshua 6:26) in Hiel''s building project function narratively at the end of 1 Kings 16?', 'It demonstrates that ancient prophetic words retain their power centuries later, providing an ominous frame before Elijah''s ministry — God''s word stands regardless of time', 'It is a historical curiosity with no narrative function', 'It condemns Hiel''s ambition but not Ahab''s', 'It shows the curse was weakened over centuries', 'a', '1 Kings 16:34 — "According to the word of the LORD, which he spake by Joshua the son of Nun." Placed immediately before Elijah''s appearance, this verse reactivates prophetic authority — if a centuries-old word proved true, Elijah''s words would prove true too.'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 6, 'What does Elah''s drunkenness when killed suggest about the moral condition of the northern court under Baasha''s dynasty?', 'It portrays a leadership characterised by dissipation rather than vigilance — a negative counterpart to the warrior-king ideal of Deuteronomy and Samuel', 'It was an isolated incident unrelated to his character', 'Drunkenness was culturally acceptable for kings', 'It shows Elah was betrayed by trusted servants', 'a', '1 Kings 16:9 — "Drinking himself drunk in the house of Arza steward of his house in Tirzah." The detail of the king being drunk while his military commander plotted treason captures the dynasty''s terminal weakness.'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 7, 'How many verses does the narrator devote to Omri — one of Israel''s most politically powerful kings — and what does this proportion reveal about the Deuteronomistic Historian''s priorities?', 'Only about eight verses — because Omri''s significance is evaluated by obedience to God rather than political or military achievement, and he was extremely wicked', 'Many chapters, showing his importance was fully recognised', 'One verse, as he was considered irrelevant', 'Half the chapter, balanced between politics and theology', 'a', '1 Kings 16:23-28 — Omri gets roughly six verses despite founding the most internationally recognised Israelite dynasty. The historian''s theological lens deliberately minimises rulers whose significance was purely political.'),
('1 Kings', 16, 'adults', 8, 'What does the establishment of Baal worship in Samaria under Ahab and Jezebel set up for the ministry of Elijah in the following chapters?', 'The theological confrontation between Yahweh and Baal — Elijah''s entire ministry addresses whether Israel will serve the God of the covenant or the storm deity Baal, climaxing at Carmel', 'A minor religious controversy quickly resolved', 'Background information with no narrative consequence', 'A political problem requiring diplomatic not prophetic solutions', 'a', '1 Kings 16:32-33 — "He reared up an altar for Baal in the house of Baal... and Ahab did more to provoke the LORD God of Israel to anger than all the kings of Israel that were before him." This verse immediately precedes the introduction of Elijah (17:1), framing his ministry as Yahweh''s direct response to Baal worship.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 17 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 17, 'kids', 1, 'What animals brought Elijah bread and meat while he hid by the brook Cherith?', 'Ravens', 'Eagles', 'Doves', 'Sparrows', 'a', '1 Kings 17:6 — "And the ravens brought him bread and flesh in the morning, and bread and flesh in the evening; and he drank of the brook."'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'kids', 2, 'What miracle happened with the widow''s jar of meal and barrel of oil during the famine?', 'They did not run out — the meal and oil lasted until rain came back to the land', 'They filled up completely overnight', 'They turned into gold', 'They multiplied into a storehouse of food', 'a', '1 Kings 17:16 — "And the barrel of meal wasted not, neither did the cruse of oil fail, according to the word of the LORD, which he spake by Elijah."'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'kids', 3, 'What did Elijah do to the widow''s son who had stopped breathing?', 'He stretched himself upon the child three times and prayed, and God brought him back to life', 'He gave him medicine he had made', 'He carried him to the city gate', 'He called other prophets to help him', 'a', '1 Kings 17:21 — "And he stretched himself upon the child three times, and cried unto the LORD, and said, O LORD my God, I pray thee, let this child''s soul come into him again."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 17, 'teens', 1, 'What bold proclamation did Elijah make to Ahab at the very beginning of his ministry?', 'That there would be neither dew nor rain in Israel except according to Elijah''s word', 'That Ahab must repent or be killed', 'That the ten northern tribes would be given to Judah', 'That Jezebel must leave Israel', 'a', '1 Kings 17:1 — "As the LORD God of Israel liveth, before whom I stand, there shall not be dew nor rain these years, but according to my word."'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'teens', 2, 'After the brook Cherith dried up, where did God send Elijah and why?', 'To Zarephath in Sidon — God had commanded a widow there to sustain him', 'To Jerusalem to hide in the temple', 'To the wilderness of Sinai to pray', 'To Egypt to find food', 'a', '1 Kings 17:9 — "Arise, get thee to Zarephath, which belongeth to Zidon, and dwell there: behold, I have commanded a widow woman there to sustain thee."'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'teens', 3, 'What was the widow of Zarephath preparing when Elijah arrived, and what was her plan?', 'She was gathering sticks to make one last meal for herself and her son, expecting them to eat it and die', 'She was preparing a feast for the village leaders', 'She was baking bread to sell in the market', 'She was cooking a sacrifice for Baal', 'a', '1 Kings 17:12 — "As the LORD thy God liveth, I have not a cake, but an handful of meal in a barrel, and a little oil in a cruse: and, behold, I am gathering two sticks, that I may go in and dress it for me and my son, that we may eat it, and die."'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'teens', 4, 'What faith challenge did Elijah give the widow before God sustained her household?', 'He told her to make him a little cake first, then make for herself and her son — trusting God''s promise that the meal and oil would not fail', 'He asked her to pray with him for seven days', 'He told her to share her food with all her neighbours first', 'He required her to travel to the Jordan River', 'a', '1 Kings 17:13 — "And Elijah said unto her, Fear not; go and do as thou hast said: but make me thereof a little cake first, and bring it unto me, and after make for thee and for thy son."'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'teens', 5, 'What did the widow say to Elijah when her son died, and what does this reveal?', 'She accused Elijah of coming to call her sin to remembrance and slay her son — revealing guilt and a belief in prophets as agents of divine judgment', 'She calmly asked him to pray for the boy', 'She said God had forsaken her because she was a Gentile', 'She asked Elijah to leave immediately', 'a', '1 Kings 17:18 — "And she said unto Elijah, What have I to do with thee, O thou man of God? art thou come unto me to call my sin to remembrance, and to slay my son?"'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological significance of Elijah being sent to Zarephath in Zidon — the homeland of Jezebel?', 'It demonstrates that Yahweh''s power and mercy extend beyond Israel even into the territory of Baal — God sustains a Gentile widow in Baal''s own country while Israel suffers under the drought', 'It was simply the closest place with food', 'It showed Elijah was sympathetic to Jezebel''s culture', 'It had no theological significance beyond logistics', 'a', '1 Kings 17:9 — "Arise, get thee to Zarephath, which belongeth to Zidon." Jesus later cited this in Luke 4:25-26: "unto none of them was Elias sent, save unto Sarepta, a city of Sidon, unto a woman that was a widow."'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 2, 'How does the drought Elijah announces function as a direct polemic against Baal worship?', 'Baal was the Canaanite storm and fertility deity responsible for rain and agricultural abundance — a drought under Yahweh''s command was a direct demonstration that Baal had no power over weather', 'The drought was only a political punishment', 'It tested Ahab''s agricultural management', 'It had no connection to the Baal cult''s claims', 'a', '1 Kings 17:1 — "There shall not be dew nor rain these years, but according to my word." The drought was a frontal attack on Baal''s core domain — if Baal could not produce rain in his own territory, his worship was exposed as worthless.'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 3, 'What does the use of ravens to feed Elijah suggest about God''s providential care?', 'God commandeers unclean birds (Leviticus 11:15) — animals that would normally be ritually impure — to provide clean food, demonstrating that divine provision transcends ceremonial categories', 'Ravens were considered holy birds in Israel', 'The text is using "ravens" metaphorically for merchants', 'It shows Elijah had trained the birds himself', 'a', '1 Kings 17:6 — "And the ravens brought him bread and flesh in the morning, and bread and flesh in the evening." Ravens are listed as unclean in Leviticus 11:15. Their role as God''s caterers highlights the extraordinary nature of divine provision.'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 4, 'What does the phrase "the soul of the child came into him again, and he revived" establish theologically?', 'It affirms Yahweh''s authority over death itself — contrasting with Baal whose cult included death-resurrection mythology but who had no actual power over death', 'A natural medical resuscitation', 'A temporary suspension of death', 'A sign relevant only to the widow personally', 'a', '1 Kings 17:22 — "And the LORD heard the voice of Elijah; and the soul of the child came into him again, and he revived." This is one of three resurrections in the Elijah-Elisha cycle, demonstrating Yahweh''s sovereignty over the realm of death that Baal mythology claimed.'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 5, 'How does the widow''s concluding confession compare to the typical Israelite response to Elijah''s ministry?', 'The Gentile widow confesses "Now by this I know that thou art a man of God, and that the word of the LORD in thy mouth is truth" — greater faith than most of Israel showed throughout Elijah''s ministry', 'It was a standard polite acknowledgement', 'She remained skeptical even after the resurrection', 'Her confession was weaker than Israel''s response at Carmel', 'a', '1 Kings 17:24 — "And the woman said to Elijah, Now by this I know that thou art a man of God, and that the word of the LORD in thy mouth is truth." The irony of a Gentile widow confessing what apostate Israel denied is a powerful narrative rebuke.'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 6, 'What does the drying of the brook Cherith after Elijah had been sustained there teach about divine provision?', 'God''s means of provision are temporary and varied — He moves His servants to new places of dependence rather than allowing them to settle into relying on a fixed mechanism of supply', 'The brook dried up due to normal weather patterns only', 'It was a punishment for some sin of Elijah', 'It showed the drought was not fully under God''s control', 'a', '1 Kings 17:7 — "And it came to pass after a while, that the brook dried up, because there had been no rain in the land." The very drought God sent to judge Israel also affected Elijah''s hiding place, driving him to the next stage of his mission.'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 7, 'What does Elijah''s three-time stretching upon the child reveal about prayer and persistence in prophetic ministry?', 'It models earnest, repeated intercession — Elijah did not receive immediate results but persisted in prayer, foreshadowing his seven-time prayer at Carmel (18:43)', 'It was a standard medical procedure', 'It showed Elijah doubted God''s ability to heal', 'It was a ritual inherited from Canaanite priests', 'a', '1 Kings 17:21 — "And he stretched himself upon the child three times, and cried unto the LORD." Compare 1 Kings 18:43-44 where Elijah''s servant goes seven times before the rain cloud appears — persistence in prayer is a recurring Elijah motif.'),
('1 Kings', 17, 'adults', 8, 'How does 1 Kings 17 function as a preparation narrative for the confrontation in 1 Kings 18?', 'It establishes Elijah''s credentials through miracles that demonstrate Yahweh controls what Baal supposedly controlled — rain (drought), food supply (meal and oil), and life/death (resurrection) — making Carmel a climax, not a beginning', 'It is merely biographical background', 'It shows Elijah was unprepared for the Carmel confrontation', 'It establishes only that Elijah was physically sustained', 'a', '1 Kings 17 prepares for 18 in three ways: the drought challenges Baal''s weather domain (17:1), the inexhaustible meal and oil mocks Baal''s fertility claims (17:14-16), and the resurrection demonstrates Yahweh''s power over death (17:21-22). Each miracle previews Yahweh''s total superiority over Baal.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 18 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 18, 'kids', 1, 'How many prophets of Baal did Elijah challenge on Mount Carmel?', 'Four hundred and fifty', 'One hundred', 'Seven hundred', 'Fifty', 'a', '1 Kings 18:22 — "Then said Elijah unto the people, I, even I only, remain a prophet of the LORD; but Baal''s prophets are four hundred and fifty men."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'kids', 2, 'What happened when Elijah prayed and fire fell from heaven on Mount Carmel?', 'The fire consumed the burnt sacrifice, the wood, the stones, the dust, and licked up the water in the trench', 'The fire only burned the wood', 'The fire lit a small flame on the altar', 'The fire came down slowly', 'a', '1 Kings 18:38 — "Then the fire of the LORD fell, and consumed the burnt sacrifice, and the wood, and the stones, and the dust, and licked up the water that was in the trench."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'kids', 3, 'What did Elijah see in the sky that meant rain was coming after the long drought?', 'A little cloud like a man''s hand rising out of the sea', 'A rainbow across the whole sky', 'Dark clouds covering all the mountains', 'Lightning flashing from the east', 'a', '1 Kings 18:44 — "And it came to pass at the seventh time, that he said, Behold, there ariseth a little cloud out of the sea, like a man''s hand."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 18, 'teens', 1, 'What famous question did Elijah ask the people of Israel on Mount Carmel before the contest?', '"How long halt ye between two opinions? if the LORD be God, follow him: but if Baal, then follow him"', '"How long will you disobey the law of Moses?"', '"How many of you will fight for the LORD today?"', '"Why have you abandoned the temple in Jerusalem?"', 'a', '1 Kings 18:21 — "And Elijah came unto all the people, and said, How long halt ye between two opinions? if the LORD be God, follow him: but if Baal, then follow him. And the people answered him not a word."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'teens', 2, 'What did the prophets of Baal do to try to get their god to answer?', 'They leaped upon the altar, cried aloud, and cut themselves with knives and lancets until blood gushed out', 'They sang psalms and burned incense', 'They fasted for three days and nights', 'They built a larger altar and offered more sacrifices', 'a', '1 Kings 18:26,28 — "And they leaped upon the altar which was made... and they cried aloud, and cut themselves after their manner with knives and lancets, till the blood gushed out upon them."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'teens', 3, 'What did Elijah mockingly suggest might be keeping Baal from answering?', 'That Baal was talking, pursuing, on a journey, or asleep and needed to be awakened', 'That the sacrifice was too small', 'That the wood was too wet', 'That there were too few prophets present', 'a', '1 Kings 18:27 — "And Elijah mocked them, and said, Cry aloud: for he is a god; either he is talking, or he is pursuing, or he is in a journey, or peradventure he sleepeth, and must be awaked."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'teens', 4, 'How did Elijah make the test harder for himself before calling on God?', 'He had four barrels of water poured over the burnt sacrifice three times, filling the trench around the altar', 'He used older, drier wood', 'He offered a larger animal', 'He prayed while standing far away from the altar', 'a', '1 Kings 18:33-34 — "And he put the wood in order, and cut the bullock in pieces, and laid him on the wood, and said, Fill four barrels with water, and pour it on the burnt sacrifice... And he said, Do it the second time... And he said, Do it the third time."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'teens', 5, 'What did the people say when the fire fell and they saw the LORD had answered?', '"The LORD, he is the God; the LORD, he is the God"', '"Elijah is the greatest prophet"', '"We will serve Baal no more"', '"Send us rain, O LORD"', 'a', '1 Kings 18:39 — "And when all the people saw it, they fell on their faces: and they said, The LORD, he is the God; the LORD, he is the God."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 1, 'Who was Obadiah and what had he done in secret during Jezebel''s persecution of the prophets?', 'He was over Ahab''s household and feared the LORD greatly — he had hidden a hundred prophets in caves in groups of fifty and fed them with bread and water', 'He was a priest who fled to Judah', 'He was a prophet who preached openly against Jezebel', 'He was a military captain who refused to hunt prophets', 'a', '1 Kings 18:3-4 — "And Ahab called Obadiah, which was the governor of his house. (Now Obadiah feared the LORD greatly: For it was so, when Jezebel cut off the prophets of the LORD, that Obadiah took an hundred prophets, and hid them by fifty in a cave, and fed them with bread and water.)"'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 2, 'What does Elijah''s rebuilding of the twelve-stone altar symbolise?', 'The restoration of the unity of all twelve tribes under Yahweh — a prophetic act declaring that the divided kingdom was one people before God', 'The replacement of Jeroboam''s golden calf altars', 'A return to the Mosaic law of building stone altars', 'A memorial to the twelve judges of Israel', 'a', '1 Kings 18:31 — "And Elijah took twelve stones, according to the number of the tribes of the sons of Jacob... And with the stones he built an altar in the name of the LORD." On Carmel, in the northern kingdom, Elijah symbolically reasserted the unity of all Israel before God.'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 3, 'What is the theological content of Elijah''s prayer before the fire fell, and how does it differ from the Baal prophets'' approach?', 'He asked God to act so Israel would know He was God and that Elijah had done all things at God''s word — it was a prayer for divine vindication and Israel''s return to God, not a magical formula', 'He repeated a formula seven times', 'He prayed for personal victory over his enemies', 'He asked God to punish Ahab and Jezebel', 'a', '1 Kings 18:36-37 — "LORD God of Abraham, Isaac, and of Israel, let it be known this day that thou art God in Israel, and that I am thy servant, and that I have done all these things at thy word. Hear me, O LORD, hear me, that this people may know that thou art the LORD God, and that thou hast turned their heart back again."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 4, 'What does the phrase "the hand of the LORD was on Elijah" (v.46) mean and what does he do immediately after?', 'He received supernatural strength and outran Ahab''s chariot to Jezreel — a miraculous feat demonstrating that God''s empowerment extends even to physical endurance', 'He fell into a trance and received a vision', 'He was carried in a chariot of fire', 'He rested for three days after the contest', 'a', '1 Kings 18:46 — "And the hand of the LORD was on Elijah; and he girded up his loins, and ran before Ahab to the entrance of Jezreel." Jezreel was roughly seventeen miles from Carmel — Elijah outran Ahab''s chariot to this city.'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 5, 'How does Elijah''s persistent seven-times prayer for rain connect thematically to his earlier threefold stretching over the widow''s son?', 'Both episodes show that answered prayer often requires persisting through apparent silence — Elijah models the perseverance in intercession that Jesus later taught (Luke 18:1-8)', 'Both show that prayer must use specific numbers', 'Both occur in the same location near Zarephath', 'Both involve miracles performed for Gentiles', 'a', '1 Kings 18:43-44 — "And said to his servant, Go up now, look toward the sea. And he went up, and looked, and said, There is nothing. And he said, Go again seven times. And it came to pass at the seventh time, that he said, Behold, there ariseth a little cloud out of the sea, like a man''s hand."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 6, 'What does the contest''s resolution — fire consuming even the stones, dust, and water — reveal about the nature of Yahweh versus Baal?', 'It demonstrates Yahweh''s absolute sovereignty over all elements of nature including those Baal supposedly controlled — fire, water, earth — leaving no domain for Baal to claim', 'It was simply a dramatic miracle for entertainment', 'It showed Elijah had special fire-making abilities', 'It meant Baal was a lesser but real deity', 'a', '1 Kings 18:38 — "Then the fire of the LORD fell, and consumed the burnt sacrifice, and the wood, and the stones, and the dust, and licked up the water that was in the trench." The consuming of water (Baal''s supposed element) and stone (the altar material) was a comprehensive territorial declaration.'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 7, 'What happened to the prophets of Baal after the contest and who commanded it?', 'Elijah commanded the people to seize them and he killed all four hundred and fifty at the brook Kishon', 'They fled and were never found', 'They were imprisoned by Ahab', 'They were allowed to return to Samaria', 'a', '1 Kings 18:40 — "And Elijah said unto them, Take the prophets of Baal; let not one of them escape. And they took them: and Elijah brought them down to the brook Kishon, and slew them there."'),
('1 Kings', 18, 'adults', 8, 'How does Ahab''s characterisation throughout chapter 18 — calling Elijah "he that troubleth Israel," obeying Obadiah''s message, watching the contest, going to eat and drink — portray his leadership?', 'As a passive, reactive, self-indulgent king who never takes theological initiative — his entire response to the greatest spiritual crisis in Israel''s history is to consume food while Elijah intercedes', 'As a repentant king who was misled by Jezebel', 'As a secretly faithful king constrained by political pressures', 'As a courageous military leader who respected Elijah', 'a', '1 Kings 18:17-19, 41-42 — Ahab calls Elijah a troubler, passively attends the contest, and "went up to eat and to drink" while Elijah "cast himself down upon the earth, and put his face between his knees" praying for rain — a sharp contrast in spiritual seriousness.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 19 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 19, 'kids', 1, 'Why did Elijah run away into the wilderness after the great victory at Mount Carmel?', 'Because Jezebel threatened to kill him within a day', 'Because he was tired and needed rest', 'Because God told him to leave Israel', 'Because Ahab sent soldiers to arrest him', 'a', '1 Kings 19:2-3 — "Then Jezebel sent a messenger unto Elijah, saying, So let the gods do to me, and more also, if I make not thy life as the life of one of them by to morrow about this time. And when he saw that, he arose, and went for his life."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'kids', 2, 'How did God feed Elijah when he was exhausted under the juniper tree in the wilderness?', 'An angel touched him twice and gave him a cake baked on coals and a cruse of water', 'Ravens brought him food again', 'A widow found him and fed him', 'Manna fell from heaven', 'a', '1 Kings 19:5-6 — "And as he lay and slept under a juniper tree, behold, then an angel touched him, and said unto him, Arise and eat. And he looked, and, behold, there was a cake baken on coals, and a cruse of water at his head."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'kids', 3, 'What was the "still small voice" — how did God appear to Elijah at Horeb?', 'After a great wind, an earthquake, and fire, God was not in any of those but spoke in a still small voice', 'In a rushing mighty wind', 'In a pillar of fire', 'In a thunderstorm', 'a', '1 Kings 19:12 — "And after the earthquake a fire; but the LORD was not in the fire: and after the fire a still small voice."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 19, 'teens', 1, 'What did Elijah ask God for when he sat under the juniper tree, and what does this reveal about his state of mind?', 'He asked God to take away his life, saying he was no better than his fathers — he was in deep despair after the great victory', 'He asked God to rain down more fire on Jezebel', 'He asked God to give him a successor immediately', 'He asked God to let him retire to Judah', 'a', '1 Kings 19:4 — "But he himself went a day''s journey into the wilderness, and came and sat down under a juniper tree: and he requested for himself that he might die; and said, It is enough; O LORD, take away my life; for I am not better than my fathers."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'teens', 2, 'Why did the angel say the journey Elijah was about to take required him to be well fed?', 'Because the journey was too great for him — he was going forty days and forty nights to Horeb the mount of God', 'Because he would be fasting for the entire journey', 'Because there was no food on the road to Horeb', 'Because he needed strength to fight enemies along the way', 'a', '1 Kings 19:7-8 — "And the angel of the LORD came again the second time, and touched him, and said, Arise and eat; because the journey is too great for thee... And he arose, and did eat and drink, and went in the strength of that meat forty days and forty nights unto Horeb the mount of God."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'teens', 3, 'What was Elijah''s complaint to God at Horeb, and how many times did he repeat it?', 'He said he had been very jealous for the LORD and was the only one left and they sought his life — he repeated it twice', 'He complained once about Jezebel''s wickedness', 'He listed seven grievances against the people', 'He asked why God had abandoned Israel', 'a', '1 Kings 19:10,14 — "And he said, I have been very jealous for the LORD God of hosts: for the children of Israel have forsaken thy covenant, thrown down thine altars, and slain thy prophets with the sword; and I, even I only, am left; and they seek my life, to take it away." He repeated this identical complaint in verses 10 and 14.'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'teens', 4, 'How many in Israel had God preserved who had not bowed to Baal?', 'Seven thousand', 'One hundred', 'Ten thousand', 'Three hundred', 'a', '1 Kings 19:18 — "Yet I have left me seven thousand in Israel, all the knees which have not bowed unto Baal, and every mouth which hath not kissed him."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'teens', 5, 'How did Elijah call Elisha to be his successor?', 'He found him plowing with twelve yoke of oxen and cast his mantle upon him', 'He sent him a written message through a servant', 'He appeared to him in a dream and commanded him', 'He announced his name before all Israel at Horeb', 'a', '1 Kings 19:19 — "So he departed thence, and found Elisha the son of Shaphat, who was plowing with twelve yoke of oxen before him, and he with the twelfth: and Elijah passed by him, and cast his mantle upon him."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 1, 'What does the psychological trajectory of Elijah — from Carmel triumph to suicidal despair under a juniper tree — reveal about the nature of prophetic ministry?', 'That great spiritual victory can be followed by profound emotional collapse, and that God''s response is compassionate care for the body and soul rather than rebuke', 'That Elijah''s faith was fundamentally weak', 'That victory at Carmel was not a genuine miracle', 'That prophets should not engage in public confrontations', 'a', '1 Kings 19:3-4 — After Carmel, "he arose, and went for his life" and "requested for himself that he might die." God''s response was not rebuke but twice-sent angelic food (vv.5-7), modelling pastoral care for spiritual burnout.'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 2, 'Why is Horeb significant as the location of God''s theophany to Elijah?', 'Horeb is Mount Sinai — the place of Moses'' foundational encounter with God — connecting Elijah to the Mosaic tradition and framing his ministry as a renewal of the Sinai covenant', 'It was simply the most remote location available', 'It was where Elijah had trained as a young man', 'It was the burial site of the patriarchs', 'a', '1 Kings 19:8 — "Unto Horeb the mount of God." Horeb/Sinai is where Moses received the law (Exodus 3, 19) and where the covenant was established. Elijah''s retreat there signals a covenant-renewal moment at the very source of Israel''s theological identity.'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 3, 'How does the theophany at Horeb — wind, earthquake, fire, then still small voice — contrast with Elijah''s recent experience at Carmel?', 'At Carmel God acted through dramatic public fire; at Horeb God passed by in a still small voice — teaching that divine presence is not always in spectacular power but often in quiet, direct word', 'It shows God changed His methods permanently', 'It indicates Elijah misidentified the Carmel miracle', 'It suggests the still small voice was a rebuke for the Carmel drama', 'a', '1 Kings 19:11-12 — "A great and strong wind rent the mountains... but the LORD was not in the wind: and after the wind an earthquake; but the LORD was not in the earthquake: And after the earthquake a fire; but the LORD was not in the fire: and after the fire a still small voice."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 4, 'What is the theological significance of God''s response "What doest thou here, Elijah?" — asked twice in identical form?', 'It functions as both a gentle challenge and an invitation to honest confession — God does not rebuke but draws out Elijah''s despair before giving new commission, modelling redemptive pastoral dialogue', 'It was a rebuke for Elijah''s cowardice', 'It showed God was unaware of Elijah''s situation', 'It was a formula greeting used in prophetic encounters', 'a', '1 Kings 19:9,13 — "And he came thither unto a cave, and lodged there; and, behold, the word of the LORD came to him, and he said unto him, What doest thou here, Elijah?" The question is repeated after the theophany (v.13), showing that the spectacular display did not resolve Elijah''s spiritual crisis — only recommissioning did.'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 5, 'What three tasks does God commission Elijah to perform after the Horeb encounter?', 'To anoint Hazael king over Syria, Jehu king over Israel, and Elisha as prophet in his place', 'To rebuild the altar at Bethel, confront Jezebel personally, and call a fast', 'To return to Carmel, assemble all Israel, and read the law', 'To go to Jerusalem, anoint a new high priest, and prophesy to Judah', 'a', '1 Kings 19:15-16 — "Anoint Hazael to be king over Syria: And Jehu the son of Nimshi shalt thou anoint to be king over Israel: and Elisha the son of Shaphat of Abel-meholah shalt thou anoint to be prophet in thy room."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 6, 'What does Elisha''s slaughtering of his oxen and burning his plowing equipment before following Elijah signify?', 'A decisive and irreversible break with his former life — by destroying his livelihood he burned his bridges, committing himself completely to prophetic calling', 'A farewell feast for his family', 'A sin offering required by the Mosaic law', 'A sign that farming was sinful', 'a', '1 Kings 19:21 — "And he returned back from him, and took a yoke of oxen, and slew them, and boiled their flesh with the instruments of the oxen, and gave unto the people, and they did eat. Then he arose, and went after Elijah, and ministered unto him." Jesus alluded to this in Luke 9:62: "No man, having put his hand to the plough, and looking back, is fit for the kingdom of God."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 7, 'How does the seven thousand who have not bowed to Baal correct Elijah''s isolated self-perception and what does Paul make of this passage in Romans 11?', 'It corrects Elijah''s "I only am left" with divine knowledge of a faithful remnant — Paul uses this in Romans 11:2-5 to argue that God always preserves a remnant by grace, even when outward appearances suggest total apostasy', 'It was a private word of comfort with no wider application', 'Paul uses it to argue that Israel was entirely without excuse', 'It proves the northern kingdom was secretly faithful throughout', 'a', '1 Kings 19:18 — "Yet I have left me seven thousand in Israel." Paul quotes this directly in Romans 11:4-5: "I have reserved to myself seven thousand men, who have not bowed the knee to the image of Baal. Even so then at this present time also there is a remnant according to the election of grace."'),
('1 Kings', 19, 'adults', 8, 'What parallel exists between Elijah''s forty-day journey to Horeb and Moses'' experiences, and what does this parallel suggest about Elijah''s role?', 'Moses fasted forty days at Sinai (Exodus 34:28); both received God''s word at Horeb; both fled under threat and were recommissioned — Elijah is presented as a Moses-like prophet for the covenant crisis of his era', 'The forty days was simply the travel time required', 'The parallel was accidental and has no theological significance', 'It shows Elijah was inferior to Moses in every respect', 'a', '1 Kings 19:8 — "He arose, and did eat and drink, and went in the strength of that meat forty days and forty nights unto Horeb the mount of God." This mirrors Exodus 34:28 and Deuteronomy 9:9 — forty days at Horeb is unmistakably a Mosaic typology, anticipating the Transfiguration where Moses and Elijah appear together (Matthew 17:3).');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 20 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 20, 'kids', 1, 'Who was the king of Syria who came against Israel with a great army?', 'Ben-hadad', 'Hazael', 'Rezin', 'Shalmaneser', 'a', '1 Kings 20:1 — "And Ben-hadad the king of Syria gathered all his host together: and there were thirty and two kings with him, and horses, and chariots: and he went up and besieged Samaria, and warred against it."'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'kids', 2, 'Who told Ahab that God would give him victory over Ben-hadad''s great army so Israel would know God was the LORD?', 'A certain prophet', 'Elijah', 'A priest in Samaria', 'The high priest in Jerusalem', 'a', '1 Kings 20:13 — "And, behold, there came a prophet unto Ahab king of Israel, saying, Thus saith the LORD, Hast thou seen all this great multitude? behold, I will deliver it into thine hand this day; and thou shalt know that I am the LORD."'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'kids', 3, 'What was the prophet''s judgment on Ahab for letting Ben-hadad go free?', 'His life would go for Ben-hadad''s life, and his people for Ben-hadad''s people', 'He would lose the next battle only', 'He must pay a large fine to the temple', 'He would be exiled from Israel', 'a', '1 Kings 20:42 — "Thus saith the LORD, Because thou hast let go out of thy hand a man whom I appointed to utter destruction, therefore thy life shall go for his life, and thy people for his people."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 20, 'teens', 1, 'What boastful demand did Ben-hadad send to Ahab before the battle, and what was the final demand Ahab refused?', 'Ben-hadad claimed all Ahab''s silver, gold, wives, and children; Ahab initially agreed but refused when Ben-hadad said his servants would search the palace and take whatever pleased them', 'Ben-hadad demanded half of Israel''s territory', 'Ben-hadad demanded Ahab''s entire army surrender', 'Ben-hadad demanded the ark of the covenant', 'a', '1 Kings 20:3,6 — "Thy silver and thy gold is mine; thy wives also and thy children... I will send my servants unto thee to morrow about this time, and they shall search thine house." Ahab agreed to the first demand but balked at the second, prompting his refusal.'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'teens', 2, 'How did Israel defeat Ben-hadad''s massive first army?', 'The young men of the princes of the provinces went out at noon while Ben-hadad and his kings were drinking themselves drunk', 'They sent a small raiding party at night', 'They poisoned the Syrian water supply', 'They waited inside Samaria until the Syrians retreated', 'a', '1 Kings 20:16 — "And they went out at noon. But Ben-hadad was drinking himself drunk in the pavilions, he and the kings, the thirty and two kings that helped him."'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'teens', 3, 'What did Ben-hadad''s advisors tell him after the first defeat, and what theological error did it contain?', 'They said Israel''s gods were gods of the hills, so if they fought in the plains they would be stronger — but God showed He was God of both', 'They said Israel had a stronger army that needed to be matched', 'They said Ahab had used a forbidden weapon', 'They said the Israelites had received supernatural help from Egypt', 'a', '1 Kings 20:23 — "And the servants of the king of Syria said unto him, Their gods are gods of the hills; therefore they were stronger than we; but let us fight against them in the plain, and surely we shall be stronger than they."'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'teens', 4, 'What did God say about Israel''s victory in the valley to counter the Syrian theological claim?', 'That He would deliver the great multitude into Israel''s hand so they would know that He is the LORD and not merely a god of the hills', 'That Israel was simply stronger militarily', 'That the Syrians would win in the plains', 'That He would show mercy to Ben-hadad for his humility', 'a', '1 Kings 20:28 — "Thus saith the LORD, Because the Syrians have said, The LORD is God of the hills, but he is not God of the valleys, therefore will I deliver all this great multitude into thine hand, and ye shall know that I am the LORD."'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'teens', 5, 'How did Ben-hadad appeal to Ahab after his defeat, and how did Ahab respond?', 'Ben-hadad''s servants came in sackcloth with ropes on their heads begging for mercy; Ahab called him his brother and made a covenant with him', 'Ben-hadad sent a huge ransom payment', 'Ben-hadad came personally to prostrate himself', 'Ahab refused to see Ben-hadad at all', 'a', '1 Kings 20:32-34 — "So they girded sackcloth on their loins, and put ropes on their heads, and came to the king of Israel, and said, Thy servant Ben-hadad saith, I pray thee, let me live. And he said, Is he yet alive? he is my brother."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 1, 'What does the appearance of an unnamed prophet to Ahab — a man God had appointed to destruction (v.42) — reveal about the narrator''s view of Ahab''s two victories?', 'The victories were gifts of divine grace intended to reveal Yahweh''s identity ("thou shalt know that I am the LORD") — Ahab was the unworthy recipient of mercy he squandered by releasing the enemy', 'The victories proved Ahab was a righteous king', 'The victories were purely military achievements', 'The victories showed God favoured the northern kingdom', 'a', '1 Kings 20:13 — "Thus saith the LORD, Hast thou seen all this great multitude? behold, I will deliver it into thine hand this day; and thou shalt know that I am the LORD." God gave Ahab two miraculous victories for Israel''s theological education, not because of Ahab''s merit.'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 2, 'What is the theological irony of the prophet''s parable about the man given custody of a prisoner (vv.39-40)?', 'Ahab unknowingly passed judgment on himself — the parable mirrored exactly what he had done with Ben-hadad, and when the prophet revealed himself, Ahab could not escape his own verdict', 'The parable was a general moral lesson about responsibility', 'The prophet was testing Ahab''s judicial fairness', 'The story was unrelated to the Ben-hadad situation', 'a', '1 Kings 20:40-42 — "And as thy servant was busy here and there, he was gone... And the king of Israel said unto him, So shall thy judgment be; thyself hast decided it. And he hasted, and took the ashes away from his face; and the king of Israel discerned him that he was of the prophets." The technique mirrors Nathan''s parable to David (2 Samuel 12:1-7).'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 3, 'What does Ahab''s description of Ben-hadad as "my brother" reveal about his priorities?', 'It shows Ahab valued diplomatic and commercial relationships over covenant obedience — the term "brother" was ancient Near Eastern treaty language indicating political alliance', 'It was a term of contempt', 'It showed Ahab believed in universal brotherhood', 'It indicated Ben-hadad had converted to worshipping Yahweh', 'a', '1 Kings 20:32-33 — "And the men did diligently observe whether any thing would come from him, and did hastily catch it: and they said, Thy brother Ben-hadad... And Ahab said, Go ye, bring him." The treaty Ahab made (v.34) likely involved trade rights in Damascus — commercial interest trumped divine command.'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 4, 'What does God''s response to the Syrian theological claim ("their gods are gods of the hills") reveal about biblical monotheism?', 'It asserts Yahweh''s unlimited territorial sovereignty — unlike pagan deities who were geographically or elementally limited, Yahweh reigns over hills and valleys, demonstrating that true monotheism excludes all territorial restrictions on divine power', 'It was a minor correction to a misunderstanding', 'It showed God was interested only in Israel''s geography', 'It proved that terrain determined battle outcomes', 'a', '1 Kings 20:28 — "Because the Syrians have said, The LORD is God of the hills, but he is not God of the valleys, therefore will I deliver all this great multitude into thine hand." The Syrians imposed a pagan framework of territorial deity on Yahweh; God''s answer demolished it.'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 5, 'What does the phrase "a man whom I appointed to utter destruction" (charam, v.42) indicate about Ben-hadad''s prescribed fate?', 'It invokes the cherem (devoted/sacred ban) — the same category applied to Canaanite enemies in the conquest — indicating Ben-hadad had been designated for total destruction as a divine judgment', 'It was a general statement of displeasure', 'It referred to a future defeat, not present obligation', 'It applied only if Ben-hadad attacked again', 'a', '1 Kings 20:42 — "A man whom I appointed to utter destruction." The Hebrew cherem appears throughout Joshua for enemies set apart for destruction (Joshua 6:17-18). Ahab''s release of a cherem-designated enemy was the equivalent of Saul sparing Agag (1 Samuel 15:9) — the same sin, the same type of judgment.'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 6, 'How does the structure of the two battles — one at the city walls, one in the plain — serve the narrative''s theological argument?', 'The two victories in different terrains (city walls and open plain) structurally refute the Syrian claim of limited divine power — God wins in the hills AND the valleys, systematically dismantling the territorial deity assumption', 'They are included simply as historical records', 'They demonstrate Ahab''s superior military tactics', 'They show Israel had a stronger army than Syria', 'a', '1 Kings 20:21,29 — The first battle at Samaria and the second at Aphek in the valley together constitute a two-part theological demonstration. God announced the purpose of each victory (vv.13,28) — both to reveal that "I am the LORD."'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 7, 'What do the thirty-two kings allied with Ben-hadad suggest about the political world Ahab operated in?', 'That Israel under Ahab operated within a complex system of Near Eastern vassal-suzerain relationships — the thirty-two kings were likely city-state vassals of Ben-hadad, reflecting the political structure of ancient Syria', 'That Ben-hadad was a world-conquering emperor', 'That all surrounding nations were enemies of Israel', 'That military coalitions were unknown before this period', 'a', '1 Kings 20:1 — "Ben-hadad the king of Syria gathered all his host together: and there were thirty and two kings with him." These were likely subordinate city-state rulers. By the second campaign (v.24) they had been replaced with governors — a military restructuring after the first defeat.'),
('1 Kings', 20, 'adults', 8, 'What does Ahab''s sullen reaction when rebuked by the prophet — "the king of Israel went to his house heavy and displeased" — reveal about his character across chapters 18-20?', 'It shows a consistent pattern of passive sullenness rather than repentance — at Carmel he went to eat while Elijah prayed, after Naboth''s vineyard he was sullen (21:4), and here again he is heavy and displeased rather than repentant', 'It shows Ahab was deeply humbled', 'It indicates Ahab planned to undo the treaty with Ben-hadad', 'It shows he was grieved for Israel''s sake', 'a', '1 Kings 20:43 — "And the king of Israel went to his house heavy and displeased, and came to Samaria." This matches 21:4 almost word for word: "And Ahab came into his house heavy and displeased." Ahab''s sullen withdrawal is his characteristic response to prophetic rebuke — chosen misery rather than repentance.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 21 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 21, 'kids', 1, 'What did Ahab want to take from Naboth the Jezreelite?', 'His vineyard, to make it into a herb garden', 'His house, to expand the palace', 'His cattle and sheep', 'His well and water source', 'a', '1 Kings 21:2 — "And Ahab spake unto Naboth, saying, Give me thy vineyard, that I may have it for a garden of herbs, because it is near unto my house."'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'kids', 2, 'Why did Naboth refuse to give his vineyard to King Ahab?', 'Because the LORD had forbidden him to give away the inheritance of his fathers', 'Because he did not like Ahab', 'Because the vineyard was worth too much money', 'Because he was growing food for the poor', 'a', '1 Kings 21:3 — "And Naboth said to Ahab, The LORD forbid it me, that I should give the inheritance of my fathers unto thee."'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jezebel arrange to have done to Naboth so Ahab could take his vineyard?', 'She hired false witnesses to accuse him of blasphemy, and he was stoned to death', 'She had him arrested and imprisoned', 'She paid him a large sum of money to leave', 'She declared his land forfeited by royal decree', 'a', '1 Kings 21:10,13 — "And set two men, sons of Belial, before him, to bear witness against him, saying, Thou didst blaspheme God and the king... And the men of Belial witnessed against him... and they carried him forth out of the city, and stoned him with stones, that he died."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 21, 'teens', 1, 'What was Naboth''s legal basis for refusing to sell or exchange his vineyard?', 'The Mosaic law of inheritance — land was a family''s permanent covenant portion and could not be permanently alienated (Leviticus 25:23-28)', 'He had a personal grudge against Ahab', 'The vineyard was under a Nazirite vow', 'There was no legal basis — it was purely personal preference', 'a', '1 Kings 21:3 — "The LORD forbid it me, that I should give the inheritance of my fathers unto thee." Numbers 36:7 and Leviticus 25:23 both forbid the permanent transfer of tribal land inheritance — "the land shall not be sold for ever: for the land is mine."'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'teens', 2, 'How did Ahab respond to Naboth''s refusal, and what does this reveal about his character?', 'He went to his house sullen and displeased, refused to eat, and lay on his bed with his face turned away', 'He immediately consulted lawyers about seizing the land', 'He asked the elders of Israel to mediate', 'He threatened Naboth publicly before the whole city', 'a', '1 Kings 21:4 — "And Ahab came into his house heavy and displeased because of the word which Naboth the Jezreelite had spoken to him: for he had said, I will not give thee the inheritance of my fathers. And he laid him down upon his bed, and turned away his face, and would eat no bread."'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'teens', 3, 'What method did Jezebel use to frame Naboth through the legal system?', 'She wrote letters in Ahab''s name sealed with his seal to the elders and nobles, ordering them to proclaim a fast, seat Naboth prominently, and have two sons of Belial testify that he blasphemed God and the king', 'She bribed judges directly with gold', 'She fabricated tax records showing Naboth owed the king money', 'She accused Naboth of treason before the army', 'a', '1 Kings 21:8-10 — "So she wrote letters in Ahab''s name, and sealed them with his seal... saying, Proclaim a fast, and set Naboth on high among the people: And set two men, sons of Belial, before him, to bear witness against him."'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'teens', 4, 'What was Elijah''s message to Ahab in the vineyard itself?', 'That in the place where dogs licked Naboth''s blood, dogs would lick Ahab''s blood', 'That Ahab would lose his next battle with Syria', 'That Jezebel would be removed from power', 'That the vineyard would be destroyed by fire', 'a', '1 Kings 21:19 — "Thus saith the LORD, Hast thou killed, and also taken possession? And thou shalt speak unto him, saying, Thus saith the LORD, In the place where dogs licked the blood of Naboth shall dogs lick thy blood, even thine."'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'teens', 5, 'What happened when Ahab humbled himself before God after Elijah''s judgment?', 'God delayed the judgment — He said the disaster would come in his son''s days rather than in Ahab''s own lifetime', 'God cancelled the judgment entirely', 'Elijah withdrew the prophecy', 'The prophecy was transferred to Jezebel alone', 'a', '1 Kings 21:29 — "Seest thou how Ahab humbleth himself before me? because he humbleth himself before me, I will not bring the evil in his days: but in his son''s days will I bring the evil upon his house."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 1, 'How does the Naboth narrative function as a microcosm of the theological tension between Israelite covenant law and Canaanite kingship ideology?', 'In Israel, Yahweh was the ultimate land-owner and king was subject to Torah; Jezebel''s Phoenician royal ideology treated the king as absolute sovereign over all property — the episode dramatises two incompatible views of royal power', 'It was simply a property dispute without theological significance', 'It showed Ahab had good intentions but poor judgment', 'It illustrated that Mosaic law was no longer respected', 'a', '1 Kings 21:7 — "Dost thou now govern the kingdom of Israel? arise, and eat bread, and let thine heart be merry: I will give thee the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite." Jezebel''s contemptuous question reveals her assumption that kings are absolute; Naboth''s appeal to "the LORD forbid it me" (v.3) assumes the opposite.'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 2, 'What legal requirement did Jezebel exploit in fabricating the charge against Naboth, and why were two witnesses required?', 'Deuteronomy 17:6 and 19:15 required two witnesses for a capital charge — Jezebel used the Torah''s own evidentiary standard as the mechanism for judicial murder, perverting the law meant to protect the innocent', 'One witness was legally sufficient and she provided two for emphasis', 'The witnesses were required by Phoenician not Israelite law', 'Two witnesses were needed to sign the property transfer documents', 'a', '1 Kings 21:10 — "Set two men, sons of Belial, before him, to bear witness against him." Deuteronomy 17:6 states "at the mouth of two witnesses, or three witnesses, shall he that is worthy of death be put to death." The law designed to prevent wrongful execution was weaponised to accomplish it.'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 3, 'What extended judgment did Elijah pronounce on Jezebel specifically?', 'That dogs would devour Jezebel by the wall of Jezreel', 'That she would die in exile far from Israel', 'That she would be imprisoned for life', 'That her sons would not succeed to the throne', 'a', '1 Kings 21:23 — "And of Jezebel also spake the LORD, saying, The dogs shall eat Jezebel by the wall of Jezreel."'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 4, 'How does the narrator''s editorial comment in verse 25-26 frame Ahab''s guilt in the Naboth episode?', 'It identifies Jezebel as the instigator but holds Ahab fully responsible — "whom Jezebel his wife stirred up" acknowledges her role while "Ahab did sell himself to work wickedness" makes his culpability absolute', 'It exonerates Ahab and blames only Jezebel', 'It distributes blame equally between them', 'It suggests Ahab was unaware of Jezebel''s plot', 'a', '1 Kings 21:25-26 — "But there was none like unto Ahab, which did sell himself to work wickedness in the sight of the LORD, whom Jezebel his wife stirred up. And he did very abominably in following idols." The active verb "sell himself" places ultimate moral agency on Ahab despite Jezebel''s instigation.'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 5, 'What does God''s response to Ahab''s humble repentance reveal about the nature of divine judgment and mercy?', 'That genuine humility — even from the most wicked king — moves God to delay judgment, demonstrating that repentance is never futile and that divine mercy can modify the timing if not the ultimate verdict of judgment', 'That repentance cancels all consequences permanently', 'That God could not carry out the judgment as planned', 'That Ahab''s repentance was recognised as sufficient atonement', 'a', '1 Kings 21:29 — "Seest thou how Ahab humbleth himself before me? because he humbleth himself before me, I will not bring the evil in his days." This parallels Hezekiah''s prayer (2 Kings 20:1-6) and anticipates the New Testament principle that genuine contrition moves the hand of God (James 4:10).'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 6, 'Elijah accuses Ahab: "Hast thou killed, and also taken possession?" — what double crime does this identify?', 'Murder and theft — the two crimes together represent the violation of the sixth and eighth commandments, making the episode a test case for whether the Decalogue applied even to the king', 'Only the theft of land', 'Only the judicial murder of Naboth', 'A crime against the state and a crime against religion', 'a', '1 Kings 21:19 — "Hast thou killed, and also taken possession?" Commandment six: "Thou shalt not kill" (Exodus 20:13); commandment eight: "Thou shalt not steal" (Exodus 20:15). The episode proves the Decalogue''s claim upon royal power.'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 7, 'What does the fast Jezebel proclaimed as part of her plot against Naboth reveal about the manipulation of religious institutions for political ends?', 'A public fast was a solemn religious assembly that gave the proceedings an air of divine sanction — Jezebel weaponised religious ritual to disguise state-sponsored judicial murder as community justice', 'The fast was a sign of genuine mourning', 'Fasts were routine administrative procedures', 'It was required by law before any capital trial', 'a', '1 Kings 21:9 — "Proclaim a fast, and set Naboth on high among the people." The fast gave the proceedings a legal-religious solemnity. By sitting Naboth prominently they created a public setting for his formal accusation — a travesty of genuine covenant assembly.'),
('1 Kings', 21, 'adults', 8, 'How does Elijah''s appearance "in the vineyard of Naboth, whither he is gone down to possess it" (v.18) create the maximum possible dramatic and theological irony?', 'Ahab descended into the vineyard of his victim to savour his possession — and found the prophet of God already waiting there with God''s verdict, turning the moment of triumph into the moment of judgment', 'It was a coincidence that Elijah arrived at that time', 'Elijah was inspecting the vineyard for future use', 'Ahab invited Elijah to view the land', 'a', '1 Kings 21:18-19 — "Arise, go down to meet Ahab king of Israel, which is in Samaria: behold, he is in the vineyard of Naboth, whither he is gone down to possess it. And thou shalt speak unto him." The vineyard that was stolen becomes the courtroom where divine justice is declared.');

-- ═══ 1 Kings Chapter 22 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('1 Kings', 22, 'kids', 1, 'How did Ahab try to protect himself in the battle at Ramoth-gilead?', 'He disguised himself so the enemy would not know he was the king', 'He stayed far behind the army', 'He wore the strongest armour in Israel', 'He sent a decoy dressed like him', 'a', '1 Kings 22:30 — "And the king of Israel said unto Jehoshaphat, I will disguise myself, and enter into the battle; but put thou on thy robes."'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'kids', 2, 'How was Ahab mortally wounded in the battle?', 'A man drew a bow at random and the arrow struck him between the joints of his armour', 'He was attacked by a Syrian soldier who recognised him', 'He was struck by a stone from a catapult', 'He fell from his chariot while charging', 'a', '1 Kings 22:34 — "And a certain man drew a bow at a venture, and smote the king of Israel between the joints of the harness: wherefore he said unto his chariot man, Turn thine hand, and carry me out of the host; for I am wounded."'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'kids', 3, 'Where did dogs lick up Ahab''s blood after he died, and why was this significant?', 'At the pool of Samaria where they washed his chariot — fulfilling the prophecy Elijah had spoken about his blood', 'In the city of Jezreel where Naboth lived', 'At the gates of Ramoth-gilead', 'At the tomb of Jeroboam', 'a', '1 Kings 22:38 — "And one washed the chariot in the pool of Samaria; and the dogs licked up his blood; and they washed his armour; according unto the word of the LORD which he spake."'),
-- Teens
('1 Kings', 22, 'teens', 1, 'What did the four hundred false prophets unanimously promise Ahab about the battle at Ramoth-gilead?', 'That God would deliver Ramoth-gilead into the king''s hand and he should go up', 'That he would be victorious only if he fasted first', 'That he should not go up because the time was not right', 'That Jehoshaphat must lead the attack', 'a', '1 Kings 22:6 — "Then the king of Israel gathered the prophets together, about four hundred men, and said unto them, Shall I go against Ramoth-gilead to battle, or shall I forbear? And they said, Go up; for the Lord shall deliver it into the hand of the king."'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'teens', 2, 'What did Micaiah first say when he was asked about the battle, and why was this not his real answer?', 'He mockingly told Ahab to go up and prosper — he was repeating what the false prophets said sarcastically, and Ahab knew it and demanded the truth', 'He refused to answer initially', 'He spoke in parables that no one understood', 'He said he needed more time to pray before answering', 'a', '1 Kings 22:15-16 — "And when he was come to the king, the king said unto him, Micaiah, shall we go against Ramoth-gilead to battle, or shall we forbear? And he answered him, Go, and prosper: for the LORD shall deliver it into the hand of the king. And the king said unto him, How many times shall I adjure thee that thou tell me nothing but that which is true in the name of the LORD?"'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'teens', 3, 'What vision did Micaiah describe concerning a lying spirit and the false prophets?', 'He saw all Israel scattered as sheep without a shepherd, and God asking a spirit to entice Ahab — a lying spirit in the mouth of all his prophets to lure him to his death at Ramoth-gilead', 'He saw Ahab winning a great victory', 'He saw angels going before the army to protect them', 'He saw Jehoshaphat being killed instead of Ahab', 'a', '1 Kings 22:17,22 — "I saw all Israel scattered upon the hills, as sheep that have not a shepherd... And the LORD said unto him, Thou shalt entice him, and thou shalt also prevail: go forth, and do so."'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'teens', 4, 'What did Zedekiah the false prophet do to Micaiah and what did he claim it symbolised?', 'He made iron horns and said "With these shalt thou push the Syrians until thou have consumed them"', 'He slapped Micaiah across the face', 'He tore his robe in a symbolic act of judgment', 'He presented a bowl of blood before the king', 'a', '1 Kings 22:11 — "And Zedekiah the son of Chenaanah made him horns of iron: and he said, Thus saith the LORD, With these shalt thou push the Syrians, until thou have consumed them."'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'teens', 5, 'What was the reign of Jehoshaphat noted for in his summary at the end of the chapter?', 'He did right in the eyes of the LORD, walked in the way of Asa his father, removed the sodomites from the land, and the high places were not taken away', 'He made a permanent alliance with the northern kingdom', 'He rebuilt the temple in Jerusalem', 'He conquered Edom and Moab', 'a', '1 Kings 22:43-46 — "And he walked in all the ways of Asa his father; he turned not aside from it, doing that which was right in the eyes of the LORD: nevertheless the high places were not taken away... And the remnant of the sodomites, which remained in the days of his father Asa, he took out of the land."'),
-- Adults
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 1, 'What does Micaiah''s vision of Israel scattered as "sheep that have not a shepherd" function as within the broader narrative of 1 Kings?', 'It is the death oracle for Ahab — "these have no master" announces leaderless Israel after the battle, and it concludes the Ahab narrative that began with Jezebel''s introduction, completing the judgment arc of chapters 16-22', 'It was a general lament about Israel''s spiritual state', 'It referred to the period of the judges rather than Ahab', 'It predicted the Assyrian exile specifically', 'a', '1 Kings 22:17 — "I saw all Israel scattered upon the hills, as sheep that have not a shepherd: and the LORD said, These have no master: let them return every man to his house in peace." The phrase "no master" is the death sentence delivered in narrative code before the battle.'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 2, 'What does the heavenly council scene (vv.19-23) reveal about the nature of false prophecy in the Deuteronomistic framework?', 'That God can sovereignly permit deceptive prophecy as an instrument of judicial hardening — the false prophets were not simply mistaken but were divinely sent with a lying spirit as part of God''s judgment on Ahab''s determined unbelief', 'That false prophecy is beyond God''s control', 'That Zedekiah and the four hundred were Baal worshippers', 'That Micaiah was the only genuine prophet in Israel', 'a', '1 Kings 22:22-23 — "And the LORD said unto him, Thou shalt entice him, and thou shalt also prevail: go forth, and do so. Now therefore, behold, the LORD hath put a lying spirit in the mouth of all these thy prophets, and the LORD hath spoken evil concerning thee." Compare Isaiah 6:9-10 and 2 Thessalonians 2:11 for parallel themes of judicial deception.'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 3, 'What does Ahab''s decision to imprison Micaiah and proceed to battle despite his prophecy reveal about the nature of unbelief?', 'That Ahab wanted prophetic validation, not prophetic truth — he summoned four hundred prophets and then Micaiah, but when the truth contradicted his desire, he imprisoned the truth-teller and chose the pleasing lie', 'That Ahab was incapable of understanding prophecy', 'That imprisonment was the standard response to unwanted prophecy', 'That Ahab genuinely believed Micaiah was wrong', 'a', '1 Kings 22:26-27 — "And the king of Israel said, Take Micaiah, and carry him back unto Amon the governor of the city, and to Joash the king''s son; And say, Thus saith the king, Put this fellow in the prison, and feed him with bread of affliction and with water of affliction." Ahab''s response mirrors the pattern of all who suppress inconvenient truth.'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 4, 'How does the arrow "drawn at a venture" that kills Ahab function theologically within the narrative?', 'It demonstrates that divine judgment cannot be evaded by human ingenuity — Ahab''s elaborate disguise defeated human recognition but not God''s ordained purpose; the "random" arrow was providentially directed', 'It shows Ahab''s death was accidental rather than divinely planned', 'It illustrates the unpredictability of battle without theological implication', 'It proves Micaiah''s prophecy was partially wrong', 'a', '1 Kings 22:34 — "And a certain man drew a bow at a venture, and smote the king of Israel between the joints of the harness." The Hebrew "in his simplicity" (betummo) means the archer had no particular target in mind — emphasising that the hit was not humanly directed, making divine providence unmistakable.'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 5, 'What is the literary and theological function of the detail that Ahab''s blood washed from his chariot was licked by dogs at the pool of Samaria?', 'It fulfils Elijah''s prophecy from 1 Kings 21:19 ("dogs shall lick thy blood, even thine") with the narrator''s explicit note "according unto the word of the LORD which he spake" — vindicating prophetic authority as the book''s central claim', 'It is a gruesome historical detail with no theological significance', 'It shows the people disrespected Ahab after his death', 'It fulfilled only the prophecy about Naboth''s vineyard, not Elijah''s word', 'a', '1 Kings 22:38 — "And one washed the chariot in the pool of Samaria; and the dogs licked up his blood; and they washed his armour; according unto the word of the LORD which he spake." The fulfillment formula "according to the word of the LORD" is the book''s characteristic way of validating prophecy.'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 6, 'What does Jehoshaphat''s joining of Ahab at Ramoth-gilead — despite Micaiah''s clear warning — reveal about the dangers of political alliance with apostasy?', 'It demonstrates that covenant compromise through alliance can draw even a faithful king into divinely condemned military ventures — Jehoshaphat nearly died because of his alliance with the most wicked king in Israel''s history', 'It shows Jehoshaphat was equally wicked to Ahab', 'It demonstrates that Jehoshaphat had more faith than Micaiah predicted', 'It was a neutral diplomatic obligation', 'a', '1 Kings 22:32-33 — "And it came to pass, when the captains of the chariots saw Jehoshaphat, that they said, Surely it is the king of Israel. And they turned aside to fight against him... And it came to pass, when the captains of the chariots perceived that it was not the king of Israel, that they turned back from pursuing him." Jehoshaphat almost died in Ahab''s place.'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 7, 'How does Micaiah''s slapping by Zedekiah and his subsequent imprisonment foreshadow the treatment of later prophets in Israel''s history?', 'It establishes the pattern of the rejected prophet — physically abused, imprisoned, fed the bread and water of affliction — which becomes the canonical pattern for prophets who speak unwelcome truth, climaxing in Jeremiah and ultimately in Christ', 'It was an isolated incident unique to Micaiah', 'It shows that prophets were generally protected by royal authority', 'It demonstrates that false prophets eventually acknowledged the true prophets', 'a', '1 Kings 22:24,27 — "But Zedekiah the son of Chenaanah went near, and smote Micaiah on the cheek... Put this fellow in the prison, and feed him with bread of affliction and with water of affliction." Jesus cited this pattern in Matthew 23:37: "O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, thou that killest the prophets, and stonest them which are sent unto thee."'),
('1 Kings', 22, 'adults', 8, 'How does 1 Kings 22 function as a fitting conclusion to the entire book of 1 Kings?', 'It brings together the book''s central themes — the test of the true prophetic word against false prophecy, the inevitable fulfillment of God''s judgment on Ahab, and the contrast between faithful Jehoshaphat and wicked Ahab — demonstrating that the word of the LORD always stands', 'It ends the book on an unresolved note with no theological conclusion', 'It focuses primarily on the succession to Ahab''s throne', 'It concludes by praising Ahab''s military courage despite his sins', 'a', '1 Kings 22:38 — "According unto the word of the LORD which he spake." The book closes with prophetic fulfillment as its final word — Deuteronomy 18:22 defined the true prophet as one whose word comes to pass. 1 Kings ends with exactly this validation of the prophetic word against Israel''s most wicked king.');
